1
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:15,716
My wife has been kidnapped.

2
00:00:17,120 --> 00:00:19,475
There's no ransom that I can pay.

3
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:22,476
There is only the hope of rescue.

4
00:00:22,960 --> 00:00:26,236
Yet, in spite of every attempt I've made,
in spite of heroic attempts...

5
00:00:26,360 --> 00:00:29,636
that others have made,
she remains a prisoner.

6
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:31,914
A hostage.

7
00:00:33,440 --> 00:00:36,398
And I don't know
how this story is going to end.

8
00:00:39,880 --> 00:00:41,438
<i>I first met Milly way back in the '60s...</i>

9
00:00:41,560 --> 00:00:45,189
<i>when I was starting out as a cub</i>
<i>reporter for the</i> Chicago Sun-Times.

10
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:48,394
The issue is this:

11
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:52,479
<i>The government wants this university...</i>

12
00:00:52,600 --> 00:00:54,875
<i>to turn over all the academic rankings...</i>

13
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,912
<i>of its male students</i>
<i>who are eligible for the draft.</i>

14
00:00:58,200 --> 00:01:00,236
<i>They want to take</i>
<i>the lower-ranking students...</i>

15
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:03,397
<i>and make soldiers out of them,</i>
<i>while the students with better grades...</i>

16
00:01:03,520 --> 00:01:06,353
<i>get to stay on here for a while</i>
<i>until the other ones get killed.</i>

17
00:01:08,080 --> 00:01:10,753
- <i>It is pretty bad, right?</i>
- Yeah!

18
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:12,313
<i>Now, I've got to ask the question...</i>

19
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:14,715
<i>wasn't this supposed to be</i>
<i>a democracy?</i>

20
00:01:19,040 --> 00:01:22,828
<i>Everybody, stay calm, all right?</i>
<i>Everyone, stay calm.</i>

21
00:01:22,960 --> 00:01:25,758
- All right, let's settle down here!
- <i>You have a right to protest here.</i>

22
00:01:25,880 --> 00:01:27,916
- <i>It's your right to free assembly.</i>
- Get off the stairs.

23
00:01:31,080 --> 00:01:35,232
<i>He's got a right to free assembly here.</i>
<i>This is a peaceful demonstration.</i>

24
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:37,555
- Get that out of here.
- We're not doing anything illegal.

25
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:38,999
Ma'am, you're gonna
have to come with me.

26
00:01:39,120 --> 00:01:40,109
We have a right to assemble.

27
00:01:40,240 --> 00:01:41,992
Okay, we can do this the easy way
or the hard way.

28
00:01:42,120 --> 00:01:43,235
I'm not going anywhere.

29
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:45,396
- Put your hands behind your...
- We have the right to...

30
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:47,909
You have no business
doing this right now. You're a fascist.

31
00:01:48,040 --> 00:01:51,999
Hands behind your back. All right.
Let's go.

32
00:01:56,400 --> 00:02:00,154
- So, if your name is Millicent Martinez...
- Martinez.

33
00:02:00,480 --> 00:02:04,075
Martinez. Why did I bail out
Rita Torres?

34
00:02:04,520 --> 00:02:06,317
Because I didn't want to give them
my own name.

35
00:02:07,040 --> 00:02:11,033
I'd like to work for the Cook County
Juvenile Court once I get my master's.

36
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:14,238
You didn't have to bail me out,
you know.

37
00:02:14,360 --> 00:02:16,112
- You should never have done that.
- Your master's?

38
00:02:16,240 --> 00:02:17,878
- In what?
- Social work.

39
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:19,912
So let Rita Torres get the record.

40
00:02:20,040 --> 00:02:22,554
- It was almost Rita Ginsberg.
- Ginsberg?

41
00:02:22,680 --> 00:02:24,477
In honour of my mother.

42
00:02:28,160 --> 00:02:30,390
I'm paying you back, you know.
Every penny.

43
00:02:32,880 --> 00:02:36,634
- So your mother's name was Ginsberg.
- No. But she was Jewish.

44
00:02:40,320 --> 00:02:41,514
So what are you?

45
00:02:41,640 --> 00:02:42,629
- What am I?
- Yeah.

46
00:02:42,760 --> 00:02:45,274
I'm part Mexican, part Catholic,
part Jewish...

47
00:02:45,400 --> 00:02:48,278
and I just got arrested
for exercising my right to free speech.

48
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:49,355
I'm Millicent Martinez.

49
00:02:53,680 --> 00:02:56,319
This is an interview, right? Not a date.

50
00:02:56,440 --> 00:02:59,159
Because you didn't ask me for a date,
you asked me for an interview.

51
00:02:59,280 --> 00:03:02,317
No, yeah, no... yeah.
Sure, it's an interview.

52
00:03:02,440 --> 00:03:03,998
Then why aren't you
writing anything down?

53
00:03:12,120 --> 00:03:16,636
I just have to wonder about the college
kids who flock to these radical groups...

54
00:03:16,760 --> 00:03:19,638
just because, you know,
suddenly it's hip to do that.

55
00:03:19,960 --> 00:03:22,713
And I have to wonder about people
who call themselves journalists...

56
00:03:22,840 --> 00:03:25,991
and make snap judgements based upon
appearances without careful...

57
00:03:26,120 --> 00:03:28,156
and impartial investigation.

58
00:03:30,880 --> 00:03:33,713
Boy, you really like the last word,
don't you?

59
00:03:34,320 --> 00:03:36,629
Big family. What can I say?

60
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:40,869
Yeah. Thank you for tonight.

61
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:47,036
Free speech. Not free love. Call me.

62
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:56,956
- How many?
- Six.

63
00:03:57,080 --> 00:04:00,675
I've never known anybody
to see the same movie six times.

64
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:02,119
It's a damn good movie.

65
00:04:02,240 --> 00:04:06,233
- I would have gladly bought you some.
- No, yours is good. I'm hungry.

66
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:11,236
Who on earth would give you
advice like that?

67
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:12,952
James Weston.

68
00:04:13,080 --> 00:04:15,913
He's the Washington Bureau Chief
for the <i>New York Times.</i>

69
00:04:16,040 --> 00:04:19,350
He is the gold standard.
Every young journalist in America...

70
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:21,436
I got to meet him.
When he came to Dartmouth...

71
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:24,759
"See who you marry"?
He actually said that?

72
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:28,111
Yeah, among other things. Like "Start
on small papers," and "Work hard."

73
00:04:28,240 --> 00:04:29,958
And find a Washington wife.

74
00:04:30,080 --> 00:04:32,753
You know, blue blood, Vassar girl,
finishing school. I get it.

75
00:04:32,880 --> 00:04:34,757
Actually, I think the finishing schools
came first.

76
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:38,998
But yeah, he did describe a certain type,
and I wasn't about to disagree with him.

77
00:04:39,120 --> 00:04:40,235
He sounds like a snob...

78
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:41,588
- and they all sound like snobs.
- A snob?

79
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:44,598
And you shouldn't want to be like them,
you should want to be like you.

80
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:46,153
And anybody who wants to be
somebody else...

81
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:49,636
let them be Mort Kondracke,
and not someone who's a snob. Okay?

82
00:04:50,280 --> 00:04:53,352
- Tony, cook some sense into this guy.
- Hi, babe.

83
00:04:54,080 --> 00:04:56,992
- Hi, I'm Mort.
- Morton. It's Morton. I'm sorry.

84
00:04:57,120 --> 00:04:58,269
- Hi. It's Mort.
- Tony.

85
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:00,436
- He's got the best hot dogs in Chicago.
- Nice.

86
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:02,915
Two with the works
and a couple Yoo-hoos.

87
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:04,314
Right.

88
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:08,236
This is my sister, Alex.
She lives in London with her husband.

89
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:15,269
What?

90
00:05:15,840 --> 00:05:16,875
Nothing.

91
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:21,312
This is my mother. Ida.
She was so beautiful.

92
00:05:21,440 --> 00:05:24,273
Everyone used to say she looked like
Ava Gardner. I think so, too.

93
00:05:24,400 --> 00:05:25,992
She was so beautiful.

94
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:29,754
But she had a breakdown
and she ran away.

95
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:36,989
This is my father. This is Refugio.

96
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:40,550
He was an organiser
for the United Packing House Workers.

97
00:05:40,680 --> 00:05:44,309
The union was communist,
so they said he was communist, too.

98
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:46,198
So they deported him.

99
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:50,313
The last time I saw him was through
a gate at the train station. I was ten.

100
00:05:50,880 --> 00:05:52,950
About three days later
he died of a heart attack.

101
00:05:53,560 --> 00:05:56,711
He was so strong. He was brave...

102
00:05:57,080 --> 00:06:00,197
and he always smelt of cigarettes,
I remember that.

103
00:06:02,640 --> 00:06:05,234
And I could always feel him with me,
every day.

104
00:06:05,600 --> 00:06:07,636
And I'd talk to him at night in my room.

105
00:06:09,760 --> 00:06:11,398
And I miss him so.

106
00:06:32,480 --> 00:06:36,189
<i>With a war on overseas</i>
<i>and a civil rights movement at home...</i>

107
00:06:36,320 --> 00:06:38,117
<i>there was no shortage</i>
<i>of stories out there...</i>

108
00:06:38,240 --> 00:06:40,356
<i>and I was determined to get on them.</i>

109
00:06:40,480 --> 00:06:42,835
<i>But I kept getting kicked back to Metro.</i>

110
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:46,352
<i>I was on the sidelines of life,</i>
<i>while Milly, as always...</i>

111
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:48,152
<i>was right in the middle.</i>

112
00:07:16,200 --> 00:07:17,599
- Hi.
- Hi.

113
00:07:17,720 --> 00:07:20,314
We just organised
the probation officers into a union.

114
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:22,749
The chief judge fired everybody
at the Audy Home.

115
00:07:22,880 --> 00:07:24,313
The place where they put
the problem kids?

116
00:07:24,440 --> 00:07:25,429
- Yeah.
- What?

117
00:07:25,560 --> 00:07:28,597
So I had to call the state representative
and get them all reinstated.

118
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:30,551
- And?
- And he did it.

119
00:07:32,320 --> 00:07:34,595
How about you, how was your day, huh?

120
00:08:15,040 --> 00:08:16,758
- Hi. I'm Norma.
- Hi.

121
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:19,315
I've known Milly since third grade.
Mind if I sit?

122
00:08:19,440 --> 00:08:22,318
- Hi. No, sure. I'm Mort.
- I knew that.

123
00:08:24,280 --> 00:08:25,633
Are you all right?

124
00:08:26,440 --> 00:08:28,032
You're looking a little uneasy.

125
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:31,278
No, I'm, you know,
just, maybe a little out of place.

126
00:08:31,400 --> 00:08:33,709
Nonsense. You're welcome here.

127
00:08:36,960 --> 00:08:38,837
So, Milly did all this?

128
00:08:39,440 --> 00:08:41,271
The Dons were already around...

129
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:45,029
they wanted to call the girls
the Donettes. Milly said, "No way."

130
00:08:45,160 --> 00:08:46,878
The Roulettes.

131
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:48,911
So the girls made her president.

132
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:51,998
She made all the rules.
She gave us a purpose.

133
00:09:00,760 --> 00:09:05,311
That's Carlos. He and Milly had a thing,
but not anymore. Not to worry.

134
00:09:07,440 --> 00:09:10,318
- Marry her, Mort.
- What?

135
00:09:10,840 --> 00:09:12,114
Marry Milly.

136
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:17,118
Boy, do you always go around giving
people advice you've never met?

137
00:09:17,240 --> 00:09:19,549
I do when it's the right advice.

138
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,753
Okay, so she didn't go to Vassar,
so what?

139
00:09:28,440 --> 00:09:31,432
- Who said anything about Vassar?
- You did. Milly told me.

140
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:35,359
- No, all I meant was...
- Mort.

141
00:09:37,680 --> 00:09:38,715
Marry her.

142
00:09:41,720 --> 00:09:45,030
Police brutality! Stop police brutality.

143
00:09:45,160 --> 00:09:48,755
- I got promoted, kind of, today.
- What do you mean, promoted?

144
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:51,835
Covering politics now.
There's no more Metro.

145
00:09:51,960 --> 00:09:54,793
That's great, that's great!
Because this mayor of ours...

146
00:09:54,920 --> 00:09:56,478
somebody's got to hold
his feet to the fire.

147
00:09:56,600 --> 00:10:00,070
It's in Washington. Politics.
It's not local.

148
00:10:00,840 --> 00:10:03,718
How are you going to cover
Washington politics from Chicago?

149
00:10:08,920 --> 00:10:11,992
It's what I'm interested in, Milly.
It's what I've always been interested in.

150
00:10:12,680 --> 00:10:15,433
- I don't buy it.
- What do you mean, you don't buy it?

151
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:17,437
Mort, you know all kinds of things.

152
00:10:17,560 --> 00:10:20,757
Dartmouth things, really important
things, I'm sure. But I know people.

153
00:10:20,880 --> 00:10:23,599
I know when they're lying,
I know when they're telling the truth...

154
00:10:23,720 --> 00:10:25,597
I know when they're phoney
and when they're for real.

155
00:10:25,720 --> 00:10:28,314
And that's your weakness, Mort.
You don't know these things.

156
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:30,556
You'll get to Washington
and you're going to find out...

157
00:10:30,680 --> 00:10:32,910
and it will all be too late,
because I won't be there.

158
00:10:33,040 --> 00:10:34,678
You will die there without me.

159
00:10:36,800 --> 00:10:39,473
This is something
I have to do alone, Milly.

160
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:42,194
If I were to bring you along,
if I were to bring anyone along...

161
00:10:42,320 --> 00:10:45,517
Who said anything about coming along?
Who would want to do that?

162
00:10:46,640 --> 00:10:47,629
Milly...

163
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:50,479
You've made it pretty plain.
I'd be a liability back there.

164
00:10:50,600 --> 00:10:54,354
Who wants to be dead weight? Okay,
Mort, go to Washington, be happy...

165
00:10:54,600 --> 00:10:56,955
be fruitful and multiply or
whatever it is you're gonna do.

166
00:10:57,080 --> 00:10:58,399
Milly, just wait.

167
00:10:58,520 --> 00:11:00,556
If you haven't noticed,
we're doing something here.

168
00:11:02,800 --> 00:11:05,872
And in case you're wondering,
we just broke up.

169
00:11:06,440 --> 00:11:09,512
Stop corrupt police!
Power to the people!

170
00:11:16,680 --> 00:11:19,558
Kondracke, the <i>Chicago Sun-Times.</i>
I've been waiting for over an hour.

171
00:11:19,680 --> 00:11:22,990
I know that, Mr Kondracke. I've already
told you, the senator has had a big...

172
00:11:23,120 --> 00:11:25,076
- He cares about gun control.
- Of course he does.

173
00:11:25,200 --> 00:11:28,351
And since I'm writing a story on
gun control, or at least I'm trying to...

174
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:29,674
So is he. Excuse me.

175
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:31,472
- Thank you.
- Yes.

176
00:11:33,560 --> 00:11:34,834
Fred Barnes.

177
00:11:35,840 --> 00:11:37,592
- <i>Baltimore Sun.</i>
- Right.

178
00:11:38,040 --> 00:11:40,395
Mort Kondracke.
I've read some of your work.

179
00:11:40,520 --> 00:11:43,080
- Can't say I agree with it, but...
- Same here.

180
00:11:45,320 --> 00:11:46,469
So how did you do that?

181
00:11:47,720 --> 00:11:48,869
- How did I do what?
- How did...

182
00:11:50,200 --> 00:11:52,316
- Well, how did you...
- See you around.

183
00:12:09,680 --> 00:12:12,194
Can I have one with everything,
and a Yoo-hoo?

184
00:12:12,320 --> 00:12:14,390
- Hey, Tony, how are you doing?
- Mr <i>Sun-Times.</i>

185
00:12:14,520 --> 00:12:15,839
- Yeah.
- Where you been?

186
00:12:15,960 --> 00:12:17,996
- Washington.
- You back now?

187
00:12:18,200 --> 00:12:21,158
Just for a couple days. I'm here to
help them set up the election coverage.

188
00:12:37,240 --> 00:12:39,117
- Close, huh?
- Yeah, no cigar.

189
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:44,994
They don't have hot dogs
in Washington?

190
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:48,588
Hey, now.

191
00:12:49,760 --> 00:12:51,478
Not like they do here.

192
00:13:26,800 --> 00:13:30,679
It just doesn't make sense.
I'm not supposed to love you. I'm not...

193
00:13:31,480 --> 00:13:33,675
I don't want to love you, and then I...

194
00:13:33,800 --> 00:13:38,078
I see you in that stupid raincoat with
your legs sticking out, and then all...

195
00:13:38,800 --> 00:13:40,119
None of the other stuff makes sense.

196
00:13:40,240 --> 00:13:41,434
What do you mean? What raincoat?

197
00:13:41,560 --> 00:13:44,438
Well, how many do you have?
The yellow one. That yellow thing.

198
00:13:44,560 --> 00:13:48,519
When I went to pick you up in the rain,
and I saw you standing...

199
00:13:48,920 --> 00:13:53,755
And everything that I was convinced
that I wanted just went out the window.

200
00:13:53,880 --> 00:13:56,348
And I wanted to tell you right
then and there that I loved you.

201
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:02,194
- So you love me, but you'd rather not.
- I'd rather marry you. You know?

202
00:14:03,520 --> 00:14:05,829
I'm brushing my teeth the other night,
I had this image.

203
00:14:05,960 --> 00:14:09,509
I'm walking down the Capitol steps,
you're coming up and you're...

204
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:13,748
on the arm of this... Someone else,
a senator, and I'm an idiot.

205
00:14:14,160 --> 00:14:17,550
And I just don't want to spend my life
being an idiot.

206
00:14:17,720 --> 00:14:19,472
So do you want to marry me
because you love me...

207
00:14:19,600 --> 00:14:21,716
or because you don't want to see me
marry some senator...

208
00:14:21,840 --> 00:14:23,068
who might have a better life than you?

209
00:14:23,960 --> 00:14:25,234
Because I love you.

210
00:14:26,560 --> 00:14:28,039
Say that again.

211
00:14:29,280 --> 00:14:30,474
I love you.

212
00:14:35,400 --> 00:14:39,359
And nothing else matters but that.

213
00:14:43,360 --> 00:14:46,193
<i>Milly always talked about</i>
<i>how she thought it was fate...</i>

214
00:14:46,320 --> 00:14:48,276
<i>that brought us back together.</i>

215
00:14:48,480 --> 00:14:52,268
<i>That it wasn't just the day she came</i>
<i>home early when I was back in town.</i>

216
00:14:52,400 --> 00:14:55,198
<i>And even though it was no accident</i>
<i>that I was in her neighbourhood...</i>

217
00:14:55,320 --> 00:14:57,709
<i>she said it was fate all the same.</i>

218
00:14:58,400 --> 00:15:03,315
<i>I just knew for the first time ever,</i>
<i>that I was happy and completely in love.</i>

219
00:15:04,560 --> 00:15:07,996
For peace in this world
and justice in this country.

220
00:15:08,280 --> 00:15:10,077
For now and forever.

221
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:14,390
- For the rest of our lives.
- For the rest of our lives.

222
00:15:14,680 --> 00:15:17,240
I now pronounce you husband and wife.

223
00:15:17,800 --> 00:15:19,518
You may kiss your bride.

224
00:15:38,520 --> 00:15:42,308
<i>What I remembered most about</i>
<i>that day is finally feeling confident...</i>

225
00:15:43,360 --> 00:15:47,069
<i>utterly satisfied that I'd just made</i>
